To calculate the determinant of the product of matrices \( \mathbf{A} \) and \( \mathbf{B} \), we first need to find the product of the matrices. The product of two matrices is found by multiplying the corresponding elements in each row of the first matrix by the corresponding elements in each column of the second matrix, and then summing the products.

The product of matrices \( \mathbf{A} \) and \( \mathbf{B} \) is given by:
$$
\mathbf{A B} = \begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & 3 & 1 \\
2 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
2 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 2 \\
1 & 1 & 3
\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}
2 & 1 & 0 \\
-1 & 3 & 1 \\
3 & 1 & 2
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Now, we can calculate the determinant of the product matrix \( \mathbf{A B} \):
$$
|\mathbf{A B}| = \begin{vmatrix}
2 & 1 & 0 \\
-1 & 3 & 1 \\
3 & 1 & 2
\end{vmatrix}
= 2(3 \cdot 2 - 1 \cdot 1) - 1(-1 \cdot 2 - 3 \cdot 3) + 0(-1 \cdot 1 - 3 \cdot 3)
= 2(6 - 1) - 1(-2 + 9) + 0(-1 - 9)
= 2(5) + 1(7) + 0(-10)
= 10 + 7 + 0
= 17
$$

Therefore, the determinant of the product of matrices \( \mathbf{A} \) and \( \mathbf{B} \) is \( |\mathbf{A B}| = 17 \).
